in total from 5 different hands; ownership note from the 17th century on the front mirror: [Belongs to ] S: Katharina Kloster:         
f.449r: pray to God for the two sisters with the ave mary who decorated this book with great work and a dexterous hand, as one can clearly see S. potentiana t[almann] and S. efrosina k[eller]
Five hands write: 1. f.1r - 120v , 2. 120v - 147v , 243v , 3. 137v - 188v , 244 - 448r , 4. 189r - 243r , 5. 448r . The third is the dated one, with the colophon quoted above; the fifth only writes the second colophon. It is not possible to assign the two sisters mentioned to two of the five hands, since no other subscribed manuscripts are known from either of them. See list of scribes.

1st hand (see CMD-CH III, Fig. 447) f.1r - 121r : semi-cursive bastarda of a hand used to writing and experienced, identical to the hand of Cod. sang. 1919 and the hand of Wil M 42 ; a and u "on point", uncial d with flat belly, the g descender ends at the loop attachment, upper loops at b, h, k and l, pretzel-shaped finalis-s, st-ligature, (passim strong) backward-inclined r;
2nd hand f.121v - 138v (change of hand in the running text and sentence, on the 4th line from the bottom), f.245r (except for the top 2 lines): the hand according to the handwriting comparison is identical with the 2nd hand in Cod. sang. 1066 (for handwriting characterization see there; see CMD-CH III, fig. 448) as well as with the main hand of Cod. sang. 1916 , with passim slight deviations in the ductus;
3rd hand for 138v - 189v (passim line-by-line alternation with the 2nd hand), for 245v - 448v , by the same hand also the dating colophon for 448v / 449r (with viscous, poorly flowing rubrication ink); this hand (= the dating colophon for 448v / 449r ) is, according to handwriting comparison, identical with the hand of the Cod. sang. 1854 (for handwriting characterization see there and CMD-CH III, Fig. 449);
4th hand (see CMD-CH III, fig. 450), f.190r - 245r : strictly vertical Bastarda with narrow letter spacing, but generous line spacing; this hand without "feminine" graphological characteristics, hardly any italic elements (no upper loops), only the a "standing on point", noteworthy is the g-descender extending far downwards, vertical r with small foot to the right, occasional classic us-shortening;
5th hand below the colophon f.449r (see below), in semi-cursive bastarda, correction entry (see CMD-CH III (1991), fig. 451): text insertion to f.414r , with the same insertion mark, f.449r 4th line from the top, by the hand of Euphrosina Keller (since, according to handwriting comparison, not identical with the supplementary hand of Potentiana Talmann in the calendar of Wil M XVII). Characteristics of her hand: no upper loops at l and h, round a, backward-slanting r, e with belly almost on the line, uncial d with short flag to the left.

