3. Ox head, f.22 , with horizontally protruding, spoon-shaped (longish-round) ears and strikingly large nostrils (same size as the eyes), corresponding additional mark (pole with star?) not verifiable; similar to Piccard , watermark II/2 (1966), section VII, no. 282, more distantly similar also no. 286 (among others Basel, Konstanz, 1455-1457);
4. f.165ff., f.255 , f.262 , f.264 , f.271 a mark that is difficult to define: two crossing, double-contoured rods, probably a pair of scissors, too little visible for precise identification;
5. f.283f., f.274 Gothic P, only partially visible, do. f.284 , f.287 , f.290 ;
6. f.331 and 314 fragments of a hip horn, never completely visible (always in the fold), do. f.429 , f.437 , until the end, traced in pencil on f.442v .

